<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-117-115 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 378 117</DOCID><JOURNAL>M.D. Computing  July-August 1991 v8 n4 p208(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A new format for the medical record. (Clinical Computing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bishop, Charles W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A computerized medical record system can consist of four parts:administrative data, patient synopsis, chronological medicalrecord and detailed medical record.andP;  In order to preserve patientprivacy, the patient would be identified only in theadministrative portion of the record.andP;  Standardized phraseologycould allow easier data flow from one medical record to another,thus facilitating the construction of disease profiles.andP;  Recentmedical management can be described in detail by continuallyupdating the patient record.andP;  This 'FrameMed' four-part medicalrecord system makes it possible to retrieve background informationon patients who may otherwise arrive for care with virtually nobackground information such as chronic afflictions, allergies ormedications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsNew TechniqueMedical RecordsInformation Resources ManagementInformation ScienceData Base Management Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   A typical patient synopsis, illustrating abbreviated narrativesummary. (table)Excerpt from a chronological medical record. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>